"Adams B.D., Chen A.","The role of palladium in a hydrogen economy",2011,"Materials Today","14","6",,"282","289",,,10.1016/S1369-7021(11)70143-2,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79957979627&partnerID=40&md5=cea6b12273fdba95346be7578dba5689","Department of Chemistry, Lakehead University, 955 Oliver Road, Thunder Bay, ON P7B 5E1, Canada","Adams, B.D., Department of Chemistry, Lakehead University, 955 Oliver Road, Thunder Bay, ON P7B 5E1, Canada; Chen, A., Department of Chemistry, Lakehead University, 955 Oliver Road, Thunder Bay, ON P7B 5E1, Canada","We are facing accelerated global warming due to the accumulation of greenhouse gases. A hydrogen-based economy is one potential approach toward maintaining our standard of living while lowering carbon dioxide emissions. Palladium is a unique material with a strong affinity to hydrogen owing to both its catalytic and hydrogen absorbing properties. Palladium has the potential to play a major role in virtually every aspect of the envisioned hydrogen economy, including hydrogen purification, storage, detection, and fuel cells. Major aspects of current research and potential applications of palladium-based nanomaterials in various hydrogen technologies are presented in this review. © 2011 Elsevier Ltd.",,"Carbon dioxide emissions; Hydrogen absorbing; Hydrogen economy; Hydrogen purification; Hydrogen technologies; Hydrogen-based economy; Nano-materials; Potential applications; Standard of living; Carbon dioxide; Fuel cells; Fuel economy; Fuel purification; Fuel storage; Global warming; Greenhouse gases; Hydrogen; Hydrogen storage",,,,,,"Chen, P., Zhu, M., (2008) Mater Today, 11, p. 36; Van Den Berg, A.W.C., Areán, C.O., (2008) Chem Commun, p. 668; Chen, A., Holt-Hindle, P., (2010) Chem Rev, 110, p. 3767; Cser, L., (2004) Appl Phys Lett, 85, p. 1149; Schlapbach, L., Züttel, A., (2001) Nature, 414, p. 353; Narehood, D.G., (2009) Int J Hydrogen Energ, 34, p. 952; Kishore, S., (2005) J Alloy Compd, 389, p. 234; Y